success.question_text:
What is the cost of ten of these pens?

Type the number of dollars in the box below without the $ sign, e.g. 13.20 for $13.20.
success.question_hint:
• Work out how many are in 3 dozen.
  • Find the cost of one pen by dividing the cost by the answer and then multiplying by 10.

stimulus_2.text: The cost of three dozen pens is $21.60.

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

The unitary method is used to find the cost, say, of a number of items when the cost of a different number of those items is known. First find the cost of one item.

success.question_text: Which could be the number of dogs in the city?
success.question_hint:
• You need to find which of the four options is closest to four million.
  • Subtract each option from 4 000 000 to find the smallest difference.

stimulus_2.text: In a recent report the number of registered dogs in a city was given as 4 million to the nearest million.

review_3.column_1_text:
Round each option to the nearest million:

  • 4 552 908 = 5 000 000 to the nearest million
  • 3 099 826 = 3 000 000 to the nearest million
  • 3 472 564 = 3 000 000 to the nearest million
  • 3 781 904 = 4 000 000 to the nearest million.

Of the options, the number of dogs in the city could be 3 781 904.

Tip

When rounding off, if the next digit after the required one is five or higher, round up.

success.question_hint:
• You can compare decimals easily when they have the same number of decimal places.
  • Think of where the decimal would be positioned on a number line.

• Convert three-quarters to a decimal.
  • Divide 4 by each of the options to work out which gives an answer greater than three-quarters.

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

To compare many fractions, convert them all to decimals.

success.question_hint:
• To find the number that is halfway is to find the average of 0.9 and 1.2.
  • You need to add the numbers and divide the total by 2.

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

The number halfway between two others is the average of the two numbers.

success.question_text: Which number is not equal to the other three?
success.question_hint:
• Express each option as a decimal.
  • Three of the decimals will be the same.

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

Per cent means out of a hundred.

success.question_hint:
• Divide by 2 to find one-third of the number and then multiply by 3 to find the number.
  • To find three-quarters of the number you can use 3 ÷ 4 × the number.

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

Read the question carefully and make sure you answer the question that has been asked.

success.question_text: Who had the highest percentage success rate?
success.question_hint:
• For each girl work out the fraction of attempts that were goals.
  • The fractions are multiplied by 100 to work out the percentage.

stimulus_2.text:
In a basketball game Alice, Bree, Callie and Dinah all scored goals.

Alice scored 3 goals from 5 attempts.

Bree scored 5 goals from 9 attempts.

Callie scored 7 goals from 11 attempts.

Dinah scored 2 goals from 3 attempts.

review_4.column_1_text:
Tip

To convert any amount into a percentage, multiply by 100%.

success.question_text: What was the value of the house 10 years ago?
success.question_hint:
• Look at each of the options.
  • Find 50% of each option and add it on to see which has an answer of $480 000.

stimulus_2.text: The value of a house increased by 50% over the last 10 years. The new value is $480 000.

review_4.column_1_text:
Tip

Think carefully and don’t rush into answering a question. For example, in this question the increase is not 50% of $480 000.

success.question_hint:
• The denominator needs to be worked out before it divides into the numerator.
  • You can use your grouping symbols: 215.3 ÷ (17.4 × 6.74).

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

Make sure you know how to use your calculator to always get the right answer.

success.question_text:
How much money was initially invested in the business?

Type the number of dollars in the box below without the $ sign, e.g. 45 for $45.
success.question_hint:
• You need to find 100% of the investment.
  • From 60% you can find 10% by dividing by 6, then multiply to find 100%.

stimulus_2.text: When Hui and Samantha started their business, Samantha invested $24 000. This was 60% of the total initial investment.

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

Always check that your answer makes sense. For example, in this question an initial investment less than $24 000 did not make sense.

success.question_hint:
• Start with the bigger number and subtract the smaller.
  • You can use the (–) button on the calculator.

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

The difference between any two numbers is the result of subtracting the smaller number from the larger one.

success.question_hint:
• 57 × 34 and 18 × 57 both involve 57.
  • The two expressions are being subtracted so you can subtract 18 from 34.

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

Watch out for ways to simplify questions. For example, the idea used in this question is called the distributive law and is often used to make questions simpler.

success.question_text:
How old is Kay?

Type the number of years in the box below.
success.question_hint:
• You can use guess and check (trial and error).
  • You could start with Kay aged 12, work out the ages of the other two girls and see if the total is 44.

stimulus_2.text: Kay is 3 years older than Tabitha, but 2 years younger than Urvashi. The sum of all their ages is 44.

review_4.column_1_text:
Tip

Sometimes you can use trial and error to find an answer. For example, in this question if Kay was 10 then Tabitha would be 7 and Urvashi 12. The sum of their ages would be 29 which is not high enough, so Kay must be older than 10.

success.question_category_path: Numeracy / Number / Squares and Square Roots
success.question_hint:
• You can use the x2 button on the calculator for 202 and 122.
  • To find the missing number you will need to use the square root key.

• Work out the total number of cars in Ajak’s collection.
  • As 16 + 4 is 20, there will be 20 cars in each row.

stimulus_2.text: Ajak has his model car collection in a display of 15 rows with 16 cars in each row. He decides to rearrange the display so that there will now be four more cars in each row.

review_4.column_1_text:
Tip

When solving a problem, read the question carefully (more than once if necessary). Always check that your answer makes sense. For example, in this question there were more cars in each row so there must be fewer rows.
